date=March 30, 2020 |location=United States |date=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[Shelley Hennig]]\n| [[List_of_Days_of_Our_Lives_characters_#(1990s)#Stephanie_Johnson|Stephanie Johnson]]\n| October 2020\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of previous Days of Our Lives cast members|List of previous ''Days of Our Lives'' cast members]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Days of Our Lives}}\n{{Days of Our Lives characters}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Days of Our Lives cast members, List of}}\n[[Category:Lists of actors by soap opera television series|Days of our Lives]]\n[[Category:Days of Our Lives]]\n", "name_user": "JJonathan1989", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDebuting", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Days_of_Our_Lives_cast_members"}
{"title_page": "Bridgend Farmhouse Community Project", "text_new": "{{short description|Community-owned charitable organization in Edinburgh, Scotland}}\n{{Infobox organization\n| name            = Bridgend Farmhouse Community Project\n| image           = File:Bridgend Inspiring Growth logo.jpg \n| caption         = '''Bridgend Inspiring Growth'''\n| founders         = Will Golding, John Knox, Anna Danby, Sally Swann\n| type            = Community owned charitable organisation\n| tax_id          = \n| registration_id =\n| founded_date    = {{Start date|03/10/2010}}\n| location        = 41 Old Dalkeith Road, Edinburgh, EH16 4TE, Scotland\n| coordinates     = {{Coord|55.9268|N|3.1538|W|display=inline,title}}\n| origins         = \n| key_people      = \n| area_served     = South-east Edinburgh\n| products        = \n| services        =\n| focus           = To advance community development through the shared ownership of Bridgend Farmhouse and providing opportunities for active citizenship and volunteering\n| mission         = \n| method          = \n| revenue         = \n| endowment       = \n| num_volunteers  = \n| num_employees   = \n| num_members     = \n| subsid          = \n| owner           = \n| motto           = Learning, working and growing together to develop a flourishing community and place\n| former name     =\n| homepage        = www.bridgendfarmhouse.org.uk\n | footnotes       = \n}}'''The Bridgend Farmhouse Community Project''' in [[Edinburgh]], Scotland is a community-owned and community-run charitable organisation. The project restored an 18th century farmhouse to provide a community meeting place, caf\u00e9, garden and workshops. The project runs classes, workshops and training courses in a variety of crafts and skills aimed at all age groups. It also provides facilities for performances, gatherings, talks, entertainment and small conferences. Given charitable status under the title '''Bridgend Inspiring Growth''' (BIG), the project was one of the first in Scotland to achieve community ownership in an urban setting. In 2018 it became the first organisation in Scotland to transfer from a [[Scottish Charitable Incorporated Organisation]] (SCIO) to a [[Co-operative and Community Benefit Societies Act 2014|Community Benefit Society]] with charitable status.\n[[File:Bridgend Farmhouse from the Road.jpg|250px|thumb|right|upright|Bridgend Farmhouse]]\n\n== Site history ==\nThe site has had buildings since the 16th century. According to the 1792 history of the area by the minister of [[Liberton, Edinburgh|Liberton]], Rev Thomas Whyte, [[James V of Scotland|James V]] of Scotland built a hunting lodge on the site, adjoining which was 'a handsome chapel'<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Whyte|first=Thomas|date=1792|orig-year=|title=An account of the parish of Liberton in Mid-Lothian, or County of Edinburgh|url=http://archaeologydataservice.ac.uk/archiveDS/archiveDownload?t=arch-352-1/dissemination/pdf/arch_scot_vol_001/01_292_388.pdf|journal=Archaeol Scot|volume=1|pages=335|via=Archaeology Data Service}}</ref> which was probably built  around 1518 by Sir Simon Preston of Craigmillar, whose family owned the estate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.southedinburgh.net/history/greater-liberton-heritage-project/bridgend|title=Bridgend Medieval Chapel - South Edinburgh Net :: South Edinburgh's Community Network|website=www.southedinburgh.net|access-date=2018-10-25}}</ref> The chapel was built 'for the health of the souls' of [[James III of Scotland|King James III]] and [[James IV of Scotland|King James IV]] . In the 18th century the chapel building was being used as a stable<ref name=\":0\" />   and this was still the case in 1843, according to [[Archibald Fullarton|Fullarton]]'s Gazetteer.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The topographical, statistical, and historical gazetteer of Scotland ...|last=|first=|publisher=Fullarton & Co|year=1843|isbn=|location=Glasgow|pages=264|hdl = 2027/uc1.31210003489877}}</ref>   A major archeological survey of the site in 2014 confirmed there had been a significant building on the chapel site in the medieval period.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://canmore.org.uk/site/52101/edinburgh-bridge-end-farm|title=Edinburgh, Bridge End Farm {{!}} Canmore|website=canmore.org.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-10-25}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Recording Archaeology|title=The Search for Bridgend Medieval Royal Chapel|date=2014-11-20|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mfqHSqAZxfk|access-date=2018-10-25}}</ref>  The  present day farmhouse building dates from the mid 18th century and was extended to its current size early in the 19th.  It was originally  worked as a mixed dairy and arable farm but in the late 19th century much of the arable land was sold to become Dickson and Co.'s Royal Nursery. When the nursery closed in the 1960s the farm reverted to mixed arable, cattle and pig farming.<ref>{{Historic Environment Scotland|num=GDL00115|desc=Craigmillar Castle|access-date=2019-04-12}}</ref>   Latterly the farm was worked by the Binnie family and then the Darling family, who bought the land in 1962 and the house in 1965 until the council bought it in 1998 and the Darling's left in 2000.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thirdforcenews.org.uk/tfn-news/farmhouse-restored-to-its-former-glory|title=Farmhouse restored to its former glory|last=Jones|first=Gareth|date=28 Mar 2018|work=Third Force News|access-date=2018-12-09|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=g155t9iVVpo|title=Bridgend Community History|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nA social history project called 'Place, Work, Folk' was carried out between September 2017 and April 2019 to record, share and document the lived memories of Bridgend Farmhouse, funded by the Heritage Lottery Fund.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bridgendfarmhouse.org.uk/community-history.html|title=Community History 'Place, Work, Folk' project|website=Bridgend Inspiring Growth|language=en|access-date=2019-04-12}}</ref>\n\n== Origins ==\nThe project began in 2010 when a small group of local residents and  volunteers at Bridgend Allotments Community Health Inclusion Project, (later Bridgend Growing Communities) held a public meeting to discuss restoring the farmhouse, by then derelict and crumbling, into a community hub.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bridgendgrowingcommunities.org.uk/|title=Bridgend Growing Communities {{!}} Take part in community growing!|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-12}}</ref>  Planning took inspiration from the Edinburgh social reformer and town planner [[Patrick Geddes|Sir Patrick Geddes]], adopting his ethos of 'work, place, folk'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/@designforsustainability/design-and-planning-for-people-in-place-sir-patrick-geddes-1854-1932-and-the-emergence-of-2efa4886317e|title=Design and Planning for People in Place: Sir Patrick Geddes (1854)|last=Wahl|first=Daniel Christian|date=2017|website=Medium|access-date=2018-11-12}}</ref> In 2010 the group set up the charity Bridgend Inspiring Growth (Charity number SC042769), with the aim of turning the farmhouse and its grounds into a community centre focusing on the environment and outdoors and which would offer opportunities for learning, training and community development. Four years of consultation and planning for outreach, engagement events and community development followed. Malcolm Fraser gave design advice and the Glass-House Community Led Design charity advised on how community engagement activities might be developed around the design of the farmhouse, and held a workshop to progress this further.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.theglasshouse.org.uk/growing-bridgend-farmhouse-together/|title=Growing Bridgend Farmhouse together -The Glass-House Community Led Design|last=Jorgensen|first=Maja Luna|date=2016-03-24|website=www.theglasshouse.org.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-10-26}}</ref>  A community development officer was appointed in 2013 to set up outreach programmes in the nearby Craigmillar/ Niddrie  and Inch/Moredun areas.   The charity was  awarded grants from [[Historic Environment Scotland]] and the [[The City of Edinburgh Council|City of Edinburgh Council]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theedinburghreporter.co.uk/2017/07/bridgend-farmhouse-wins-heritage-grant/|title=Bridgend farmhouse wins heritage grant|last=Knox|first=John|date=July 5, 2017|work=The Edinburgh Reporter|access-date=2018-10-26|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oscr.org.uk/about-charities/search-the-register/charity-details?number=SC042769#results|title=OSCR {{!}} Charity Details|website=OSCR|language=en|access-date=2018-10-29}}</ref>    In 2014 funding was obtained from the Growing Community Assets<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.biglotteryfund.org.uk/funding/programmes/community-assets|title=Community Assets {{!}} Big Lottery Fund|website=www.biglotteryfund.org.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-10-25}}</ref> programme of the  [[Big Lottery Fund]] (BLF) to scope and further develop this idea and prepare an application for major BLF funding.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com/news/crunch-time-in-bid-to-make-farmhouse-community-hub-1-3384175|title=Crunch time in bid to make farmhouse community hub|last=|first=|date=23 April 2014|work=Edinburgh Evening News|access-date=2018-10-25|language=en}}</ref>  The property was owned at this stage by the City of Edinburgh  Council  who in 2014 agreed to give Bridgend Inspiring Growth a years 'license to use' the property.<ref name=\":3\" /> At that point weekly volunteer activity sessions started to transform the derelict site.  The charity received grants towards community development work from City of Edinburgh Council and others.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nIn 2015 City of Edinburgh Council agreed to transfer the land and Bridgend Farmhouse to BIG for \u00a31 in one of the first cases of urban [[List of community buyouts in Scotland|asset transfer in Scotland]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.holyrood.com/articles/comment/community-empowerment-hard-work|title=Community empowerment is hard work|last=Knox|first=John|date=May 11, 2017|work=Holyrood Magazine|access-date=2018-10-26|language=en}}</ref>  This was after the Council had received 14 offers for the property, the highest being \u00a3215,000.<ref name=\":4\" /> This transfer took place  before the [[Community Empowerment (Scotland) Act 2015]] came into force in Scotland.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bridgendfarmhouse.org.uk/scotsmag.html|title=All's well down on the farm ; Scots Magazine|last=Fraser|first=Garry|date=June 2018|website=Bridgend Inspiring Growth|language=en|access-date=2018-10-25}}</ref>  The title deeds ensured that the land and building must, in perpetuity, always and only be used as a community centre for learning, eating and exercise.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nIn 2015 the charity received a grant of over \u00a31 million from the Big Lottery Fund<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.biglotteryfund.org.uk/funding/grants/recipients/GB-SC-SC042769|title=Bridgend Inspiring Growth {{!}} Big Lottery Fund|website=www.biglotteryfund.org.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-11-18}}</ref> and further grants from the [[The Edrington Group|Robertson Trust]] and [[Historic Environment Scotland]].<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theedinburghreporter.co.uk/2015/11/bridgend-farmhouse-wins-1-million-lottery-grant/|title=Bridgend Farmhouse wins \u00a31 MILLION Lottery grant|last=|first=|date=November 4, 2015|work=The Edinburgh Reporter|access-date=2018-10-25|language=en-US}}</ref> Bridgend farm opened as a community centre on 24 March 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theedinburghreporter.co.uk/2018/03/bridgend-farmhouse-opens-saturday/|title=Bridgend Farmhouse opens Saturday|last=|first=|date=March 24, 2018|work=The Edinburgh Reporter|access-date=2018-10-26|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n== Restoration ==\nThe design was developed over years of consultation with BIG and the wider community. This involved community-led design workshops and focus group discussions.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nThe intention was a sympathetic restoration, reinstating traditional historic features such as the chimney stacks and sash and case windows. It included the addition of four community workshops which were built to look like traditional farm stable barns. The Farmhouse was kept true to its original structure, and many internal features such as timber roof beams, the window shutter panels, and original staircase and handrail being retained.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bridgendfarmhouse.org.uk/farmhouse-renovation.html|title=Farmhouse Renovation|website=Bridgend Inspiring Growth|language=en|access-date=2018-12-16}}</ref>\n\nThe architects were Halliday Fraser Munro,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hfm.co.uk/|title=Halliday, Fraser, Munro|website=HFM|access-date=2019-01-06}}</ref> The design team was completed by quantity surveyors David Adamson Group, structural engineers Elliot & Co, services engineer Harley Haddow and project manager Graham Harper. Cornhill Building Services were engaged as the main contractors and, with assistance from BIG volunteers in charring and cladding on the workshops, painting and decorating, and building and installing furniture and features, delivered the restored farmhouse to the project in late 2017.<ref name=\":2\"/>\n\nIn January 2019 the project was commended for a RIBA MacEwan Award in architecture for 'the common good'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ribaj.com/macewen/macewen-award-commended-2019-bridgend-inspiring-growth-edinburgh-halliday-fraser-munro-architects|title=How good architecture helped Bridgend Farmhouse fight loneliness|last=Young|first=Eleanor|website=www.ribaj.com|language=en|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ribaj.com/macewen/macewen-award-judging-and-winners-loneliness-community-coming-together-eleanor-young|title=In praise of architecture that brings people together|last=Young|first=Eleanor|website=www.ribaj.com|language=en|access-date=2019-02-04}}</ref>\n\n== Aims ==\nThe project aims to expand opportunities for learning, healthy eating and exercise to people of all ages living in the nearby estates of [[Craigmillar]], [[Niddrie, Edinburgh|Niddrie]], [[Inch, Edinburgh|Inch]], [[Moredun]] and surrounding area.\n\nSpecifically the project aims to advance:\n\n* Development opportunities in the surrounding communities.  Specifically it seeks to improve  citizenship skills. It aims to provide opportunities for  volunteers and to provide education and training  in  outdoor skills  and improve understanding of the environment.\n* Healthy living, promoting healthier lifestyle choices to improve  physical and psychological health.  It also aims to reduce  social isolation by providing a welcoming social environment\n* Understanding of the history of the area and its heritage. \n* Equality of opportunity and promotion of diversity.\n* Awareness and increased use of   Craigmillar Castle park, and provide education about and increase awareness of   biodiversity and protection of the environment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bridgendfarmhouse.org.uk/our-vision.html#|title=Our Vision|website=Bridgend Inspiring Growth|language=en|access-date=2018-10-27}}</ref>\n\n== Facilities ==\n[[File:Bridgend Farmhouse Cafe inside 2.jpg|250px|thumb|right|Bridgend Farmhouse Cafe]]\n[[File:Bridgend Bike Shed.jpg|250px|thumb|right|Bridgend Bike Shed]]\nFacilities on the site include:\n\n* An outdoor education workshop\n* A bicycle workshop\n* An arts and crafts workshop\n* A DIY workshop\n* An exhibition/meeting room\n* Outdoor stage and performance area\n* A kitchen garden\n* External barns\n* A community caf\u00e9 \n*A training kitchen<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.bridgendfarmhouse.org.uk/our-facilities.html|title=Our Facilities|website=Bridgend Inspiring Growth|language=en|access-date=2018-10-27}}</ref>\n\n== Activities ==\nActivities and projects include 'Place, Work, Folk' a local history project, which includes creating a collection of oral history recordings from local residents<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bridgendfarmhouse.org.uk/community-history.html|title='Place, Work, Folk' Community History Project|website=Bridgend Inspiring Growth|language=en|access-date=2019-04-19}}</ref>. There are two open volunteer activity sessions every Wednesday and Sunday which involve gardening, building, woodwork, landscaping, arts and crafts, cooking and other group activities<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bridgendfarmhouse.org.uk/activity-days.html|title=Farmhouse Activity Days|website=Bridgend Inspiring Growth|language=en|access-date=2019-04-19}}</ref>. The caf\u00e9 kitchen provides training courses which can lead to qualifications in The Royal Environmental Health Institute of Scotland (REHIS) Food Hygiene, and Health & Nutrition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rehis.com/|title=The Royal Environmental Health Institute of Scotland {{!}} REHIS|website=www.rehis.com|language=en|access-date=2018-10-27}}</ref> Courses can be completed toward  a Scottish Qualification Award (SQA) in ''Working With Others''.  There is also a project called 'Real Fast Food' which involves preparing healthy locally grown food and delivering it to people who are unable to get out of their house, on an electric powered bike and trailer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bridgendfarmhouse.org.uk/real-fast-food.html|title=Real Fast Food' project 2019|website=Bridgend Inspiring Growth|language=en|access-date=2019-04-19}}</ref> There have been courses in crafts, such as lime mortar pointing and gardening.<ref name=\":1\" /> Other courses have included \"Making natural cosmetics\", \"Forest skills\", and \"Intergenerational storytelling\" which created a book of shared stories.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bridgendfarmhouse.org.uk/previous-projects.html|title=Previous Projects|website=Bridgend Inspiring Growth|language=en|access-date=2019-01-06}}</ref>\n\nThere are regular community groups and classes, including a weekly singing group<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bridgendfarmhouse.org.uk/singing-group.html|title=Bridgend Singing Group|website=Bridgend Inspiring Growth|language=en|access-date=2019-08-09}}</ref>, craft club and woodwork club.\n\nThe project's Acorn Fund  supports local people and groups with their own projects on site. These have included \"Building a wormery\", \"Wood carving\", \"A singing group\", \"A seed library\", \"Film & media training for volunteers\" and \"Medicinal dhal workshops.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bridgendfarmhouse.org.uk/big-acorn-fund.html|title=BIG Acorn Fund|website=Bridgend Inspiring Growth|language=en|access-date=2019-01-06}}</ref>\n\n== Partnerships ==\nBridgend Inspiring Growth has, or has had, collaborative partnerships with the following organisations:\n\n=== Charitable organisations ===\n{{col-begin|width=auto}}\n{{col-break}}\n* Patrick Geddes Centre<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.patrickgeddescentre.org.uk/|title=The Patrick Geddes Centre - A Unique Learning and Cultural Centre for All|website=www.patrickgeddescentre.org.uk}}</ref>\n* Health in Mind <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.health-in-mind.org.uk/|title=Health in Mind - Health in Mind is a charity promoting positive mental health and wellbeing in Scotland|first=Primitive Media LLP-|last=http://www.primitivemedia.co.uk|website=www.health-in-mind.org.uk}}</ref>\n* Arts in Healthcare <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.artinhealthcare.org.uk/|title=Transforming Scottish healthcare with art|website=Art in Healthcare}}</ref>\n* The Sorted Project <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sortedproject.co.uk/|title=Sorted: drugs & alcohol addiction recovery Edinburgh|website=www.sortedproject.co.uk}}</ref>\n* Crisis <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.crisis.org.uk/get-help/edinburgh/|title=Crisis Skylight Edinburgh - Crisis - Together we will end homelessness|website=Crisis}}</ref>\n* The Welcoming <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thewelcoming.org/about/|title=About|date=17 October 2017|website=thewelcoming.org}}</ref>\n* Positive Realities <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.positiverealities.org/|title=Positive Realities (SCIO)|website=Positive Realities (SCIO)}}</ref>\n* The Real Junk Food Project Edinburgh <ref>{{cite web|url=https://realjunkfoodedinburgh.wordpress.com/|title=The Real Junk Food Project Edinburgh|website=The Real Junk Food Project Edinburgh}}</ref>\n* Caring in Craigmillar <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.evocredbook.org.uk/organisations/caring-in-craigmillar/001b00000065upyAAA|title=EVOC|website=www.evocredbook.org.uk}}</ref>\n* Bingham 50+ <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.evocredbook.org.uk/organisations/bingham-district-50-project/001b00000065uo4AAA|title=EVOC|website=www.evocredbook.org.uk}}</ref>\n{{col-break}}\n\n* Bridgend Growing Communities  <ref>{{cite web|url=http://bridgendgrowingcommunities.org.uk/|title=Bridgend Growing Communities - Take part in community growing!|website=bridgendgrowingcommunities.org.uk}}</ref>\n* Orchard Project <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theorchardproject.org.uk/|title=The Orchard Project - Bringing community orchards to cities and towns.|website=The Orchard Project}}</ref>\n* Non-stuff Industries <ref>{{cite web|url=https://nonstuff.co.uk/|title=NonStuff Industries|website=NonStuff Industries}}</ref>\n* Teens Plus <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.teensplus.org.uk/|title=Home|website=Teens+}}</ref>\n* Edinburgh & Lothians Greenspace Trust  <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elgt.org.uk/|title=Edinburgh & Lothians Greenspace Trust - Home|website=www.elgt.org.uk}}</ref>\n* [[Royal Botanic Garden Edinburgh]]  <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rbge.org.uk/|title=The Royal Botanic Garden Edinburgh|first=Royal Botanic Garden|last=Edinburgh|website=www.rbge.org.uk}}</ref>\n* Traditional Arts and Culture Scotland  <ref>{{cite web|url=https://tracscotland.org/|title=Home - TRACS|website=tracscotland.org}}</ref>\n*Lone Fathers\u2019  Edinburgh  <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.opfs.org.uk/|title=Welcome to OPFS|website=One Parent Families Scotland}}</ref>\n\n{{col-break}}\n\n=== Schools ===\n*Castlebrae High School  <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.castlebrae.org.uk/|title=Castlebrae|website=Castlebrae}}</ref>\n*Niddrie Mill Primary School  <ref>{{cite web|url=https://niddriemill.wordpress.com/|title=Niddrie Mill Primary School|website=Niddrie Mill Primary School}}</ref>\n\n=== Universities and Colleges ===\n*Edinburgh College  <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edinburghcollege.ac.uk/|title=Welcome to Edinburgh College|website=www.edinburghcollege.ac.uk}}</ref>\n*Newbattle Abbey College <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newbattleabbeycollege.ac.uk/|title=Home|website=Newbattle Abbey College}}</ref>\n*Edinburgh University <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ed.ac.uk/home|title=The University of Edinburgh|website=The University of Edinburgh}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ed.ac.uk/local/projects/dirty-weekenders|title=Dirty Weekenders|website=The University of Edinburgh}}</ref>\n{{col-break}}\n\n=== Others ===\n\n*Power of Food Festival  <ref>{{cite web|url=https://poweroffoodfestival.wordpress.com/|title=(no title)|website=poweroffoodfestival.wordpress.com}}</ref>\n*Volunteer Centre, Edinburgh <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.volunteeredinburgh.org.uk/|title=home|website=Volunteer Edinburgh}}</ref>\n*[[Cockburn Association]] <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cockburnassociation.org.uk/|title=The Cockburn Association - For Everyone Who Loves Edinburgh|website=www.cockburnassociation.org.uk}}</ref>\n*Track Scotland <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trackscotland.co.uk/|title=TrackScotland|website=www.trackscotland.co.uk}}</ref>\n*Scottish Ecological Design Association<ref>https://www.seda.uk.net</ref>\n*Edinburgh City Council Local Area Coordination teams  <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edinburgh.gov.uk/info/20079/disabilities/476/local_area_co-ordination|title=Support for people with disabilities|first=The City of Edinburgh|last=Council|website=www.edinburgh.gov.uk}}</ref>\n{{col-end}}\n\n== Governance ==\nIn 2018 BIG became the first organisation in Scotland to transfer from a [[Scottish Charitable Incorporated Organisation]] (SCIO) to a [[Co-operative and Community Benefit Societies Act 2014|Community Benefit Society with Charitable Status]] (CCBS).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mutuals.fca.org.uk/SocietyDetails.aspx?Number=7683&Suffix=CBS|title=Financial Conduct Authority. Mutuals Public Register. Bridgend Farmhouse|last=|first=|date=18 May 2018|website=mutuals.fca.org.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-11-26}}</ref> Under this model members buy shares to become part-owners of the land and project and each member has one vote.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://communityshares.org.uk/resources/handbook/community-benefit-societies|title=Community benefit societies|last=|first=|date=25 October 2013|work=Community Shares|access-date=2018-11-26|language=en}}</ref> The first Community Share Issue in 2018 raised over \u00a370,000 from 400 members<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thirdforcenews.org.uk/tfn-news/community-project-smashes-funding-target|title=Community project smashes funding target|last=Jones|first=Gareth|date=23 November 2018|work=Third Force News|access-date=2018-12-02|language=en}}</ref> and these  members  have rights to decide the future of the organisation, vote at the [[Annual general meeting|AGM]] and advise on strategic direction and management.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/edinburgh-community-buys-70-000-shares-to-rescue-farmhouse-1-4833749|title=Edinburgh community buys \u00a370,000 shares to rescue farmhouse|last=Ross|first=Shan|date=22 November 2018|work=The Scotsman|access-date=2018-11-25|language=en}}</ref>\n\nBIG has a board of twelve trustees all of whom are volunteers. At least 50% of the Trustees must live within the area of benefit and no decision can be made at a Board level without a local majority being present.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.bridgendfarmhouse.org.uk/our-journey.html|title=Our Journey|website=Bridgend Inspiring Growth|language=en|access-date=2018-11-11}}</ref>\n\nThe organisation has democratic structures which enable volunteers and members to direct the work of the project. There are three working groups which meet monthly; Buildings and Land, Activities and Events, and Business. These are a monthly forum for volunteers to work together and make collective decisions.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Awards and recognition ==\nIn January 2019 the project was commended for a RIBA MacEwan Award in architecture for 'the common good'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ribaj.com/macewen/macewen-award-commended-2019-bridgend-inspiring-growth-edinburgh-halliday-fraser-munro-architects|title=How good architecture helped Bridgend Farmhouse fight loneliness|last=Young|first=Eleanor|website=www.ribaj.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ribaj.com/macewen/macewen-award-judging-and-winners-loneliness-community-coming-together-eleanor-young|title=In praise of architecture that brings people together|last=Young|first=Eleanor|website=www.ribaj.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-12}}</ref>\n\nBridgend Farmhouse was chosen as an example of good practice in the Scottish Government's 'A Connected Scotland; Strategy for tackling social isolation and loneliness and building stronger communities' 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.scot/publications/connected-scotland-strategy-tackling-social-isolation-loneliness-building-stronger-social-connections/|title=A Connected Scotland: our strategy for tackling social isolation and loneliness and building stronger social connections - gov.scot|website=www.gov.scot|access-date=2019-04-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/politics/new-strategy-to-tackle-loneliness-launched-by-scottish-government-1-4845952|title=New strategy to tackle loneliness launched by Scottish government|website=www.scotsman.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-12}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019 the project received a 'Special Commendation' in the Scottish Council for Voluntary Organisations (SCVO) Charity of the Year awards in the 'Celebrating Communities' category.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scvo.org.uk/scottish-charity-awards|title=SCVO Charity of the year awards 2019|website=scvo.org.uk|access-date=2019-08-09}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scvo.org.uk/scottish-charity-awards/finalists-2019/celebrating-communities/p_award_bridgend-farmhouse|title=SCVO Finalists 2019 - Bridgend Farmhouse|website=scvo.org.uk|access-date=2019-08-09}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n* Speedy, Tom ''Guide to Craigmillar and its environs''. (1894) Selkirk, George Lewis and Son. p61\n* Speedy, Tom ''Craigmillar and its environs''. (1902) Selkirk, George Lewis and Son. p213-215\n* Geddie, John ''The Fringes of Edinburgh ( 1932 )'' Edinburgh, W & R Chambers.p129\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [http://www.bridgendfarmhouse.org.uk/ Bridgend Inspiring Growth website]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCo3QPKKFDd_9crdjXXp_f2g/videos/ Bridgend Farmhouse Video Archive]\n* [https://www.oscr.org.uk/about-charities/search-the-register/charity-details?number=SC042769#results Office of the Scottish Charity Regulator:. Bridgend Inspiring Growth details]\n* [https://mutuals.fca.org.uk/SocietyDetails.aspx?Number=7683&Suffix=CBS Registration of the society with the Financial Conducts Authority]\n\n[[Category:Social centres in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Charities based in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Charities based in Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Organisations based in Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Restaurants in Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Community buyouts in Scotland]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Community-owned charitable organization in Edinburgh, Scotland}}\n{{Infobox organization\n| name            = Bridgend Farmhouse Community Project\n| image           = File:Bridgend Inspiring Growth logo.jpg \n| caption         = '''Bridgend Inspiring Growth'''\n| founders         = Will Golding, John Knox, Anna Danby, Sally Swann\n| type            = Community owned charitable organisation\n| tax_id          = \n| registration_id =\n| founded_date    = {{Start date|03/10/2010}}\n| location        = 41 Old Dalkeith Road, Edinburgh, EH16 4TE, Scotland\n| coordinates     = {{Coord|55.9268|N|3.1538|W|display=inline,title}}\n| origins         = \n| key_people      = \n| area_served     = South-east Edinburgh\n| products        = \n| services        =\n| focus           = To advance community development through the shared ownership of Bridgend Farmhouse and providing opportunities for active citizenship and volunteering\n| mission         = \n| method          = \n| revenue         = \n| endowment       = \n| num_volunteers  = \n| num_employees   = \n| num_members     = \n| subsid          = \n| owner           = \n| motto           = Learning, working and growing together to develop a flourishing community and place\n| former name     =\n| homepage        = www.bridgendfarmhouse.org.uk\n | footnotes       = \n}}'''The Bridgend Farmhouse Community Project''' in [[Edinburgh]], Scotland is a community-owned and community-run charitable organisation. The project restored an 18th century farmhouse to provide a community meeting place, caf\u00e9, garden and workshops. The project runs classes, workshops and training courses in a variety of crafts and skills aimed at all age groups. It also provides facilities for performances, gatherings, talks, entertainment and small conferences. Given charitable status under the title '''Bridgend Inspiring Growth''' (BIG), the project was one of the first in Scotland to achieve community ownership in an urban setting. In 2018 it became the first organisation in Scotland to transfer from a [[Scottish Charitable Incorporated Organisation]] (SCIO) to a [[Co-operative and Community Benefit Societies Act 2014|Community Benefit Society]] with charitable status.\n[[File:Bridgend Farmhouse from the Road.jpg|250px|thumb|right|upright|Bridgend Farmhouse]]\n\n== Site history ==\nThe site has had buildings since the 16th century. According to the 1792 history of the area by the minister of [[Liberton, Edinburgh|Liberton]], Rev Thomas Whyte, [[James V of Scotland|James V]] of Scotland built a hunting lodge on the site, adjoining which was 'a handsome chapel'<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Whyte|first=Thomas|date=1792|orig-year=|title=An account of the parish of Liberton in Mid-Lothian, or County of Edinburgh|url=http://archaeologydataservice.ac.uk/archiveDS/archiveDownload?t=arch-352-1/dissemination/pdf/arch_scot_vol_001/01_292_388.pdf|journal=Archaeol Scot|volume=1|pages=335|via=Archaeology Data Service}}</ref> which was probably built  around 1518 by Sir Simon Preston of Craigmillar, whose family owned the estate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.southedinburgh.net/history/greater-liberton-heritage-project/bridgend|title=Bridgend Medieval Chapel - South Edinburgh Net :: South Edinburgh's Community Network|website=www.southedinburgh.net|access-date=2018-10-25}}</ref> The chapel was built 'for the health of the souls' of [[James III of Scotland|King James III]] and [[James IV of Scotland|King James IV]] . In the 18th century the chapel building was being used as a stable<ref name=\":0\" />   and this was still the case in 1843, according to [[Archibald Fullarton|Fullarton]]'s Gazetteer.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The topographical, statistical, and historical gazetteer of Scotland ...|last=|first=|publisher=Fullarton & Co|year=1843|isbn=|location=Glasgow|pages=264|hdl = 2027/uc1.31210003489877}}</ref>   A major archeological survey of the site in 2014 confirmed there had been a significant building on the chapel site in the medieval period.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://canmore.org.uk/site/52101/edinburgh-bridge-end-farm|title=Edinburgh, Bridge End Farm {{!}} Canmore|website=canmore.org.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-10-25}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Recording Archaeology|title=The Search for Bridgend Medieval Royal Chapel|date=2014-11-20|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mfqHSqAZxfk|access-date=2018-10-25}}</ref>  The  present day farmhouse building dates from the mid 18th century and was extended to its current size early in the 19th.  It was originally  worked as a mixed dairy and arable farm but in the late 19th century much of the arable land was sold to become Dickson and Co.'s Royal Nursery. When the nursery closed in the 1960s the farm reverted to mixed arable, cattle and pig farming.<ref>{{Historic Environment Scotland|num=GDL00115|desc=Craigmillar Castle|access-date=2019-04-12}}</ref>   Latterly the farm was worked by the Binnie family and then the Darling family, who bought the land in 1962 and the house in 1965 until the council bought it in 1998 and the Darling's left in 2000.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thirdforcenews.org.uk/tfn-news/farmhouse-restored-to-its-former-glory|title=Farmhouse restored to its former glory|last=Jones|first=Gareth|date=28 Mar 2018|work=Third Force News|access-date=2018-12-09|language=en}}</ref>\n\nA social history project called 'Place, Work, Folk' was carried out between September 2017 and April 2019 to record, share and document the lived memories of Bridgend Farmhouse, funded by the Heritage Lottery Fund.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bridgendfarmhouse.org.uk/community-history.html|title=Community History 'Place, Work, Folk' project|website=Bridgend Inspiring Growth|language=en|access-date=2019-04-12}}</ref>\n\n== Origins ==\nThe project began in 2010 when a small group of local residents and  volunteers at Bridgend Allotments Community Health Inclusion Project, (later Bridgend Growing Communities) held a public meeting to discuss restoring the farmhouse, by then derelict and crumbling, into a community hub.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bridgendgrowingcommunities.org.uk/|title=Bridgend Growing Communities {{!}} Take part in community growing!|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-12}}</ref>  Planning took inspiration from the Edinburgh social reformer and town planner [[Patrick Geddes|Sir Patrick Geddes]], adopting his ethos of 'work, place, folk'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/@designforsustainability/design-and-planning-for-people-in-place-sir-patrick-geddes-1854-1932-and-the-emergence-of-2efa4886317e|title=Design and Planning for People in Place: Sir Patrick Geddes (1854)|last=Wahl|first=Daniel Christian|date=2017|website=Medium|access-date=2018-11-12}}</ref> In 2010 the group set up the charity Bridgend Inspiring Growth (Charity number SC042769), with the aim of turning the farmhouse and its grounds into a community centre focusing on the environment and outdoors and which would offer opportunities for learning, training and community development. Four years of consultation and planning for outreach, engagement events and community development followed. Malcolm Fraser gave design advice and the Glass-House Community Led Design charity advised on how community engagement activities might be developed around the design of the farmhouse, and held a workshop to progress this further.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.theglasshouse.org.uk/growing-bridgend-farmhouse-together/|title=Growing Bridgend Farmhouse together -The Glass-House Community Led Design|last=Jorgensen|first=Maja Luna|date=2016-03-24|website=www.theglasshouse.org.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-10-26}}</ref>  A community development officer was appointed in 2013 to set up outreach programmes in the nearby Craigmillar/ Niddrie  and Inch/Moredun areas.   The charity was  awarded grants from [[Historic Environment Scotland]] and the [[The City of Edinburgh Council|City of Edinburgh Council]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theedinburghreporter.co.uk/2017/07/bridgend-farmhouse-wins-heritage-grant/|title=Bridgend farmhouse wins heritage grant|last=Knox|first=John|date=July 5, 2017|work=The Edinburgh Reporter|access-date=2018-10-26|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oscr.org.uk/about-charities/search-the-register/charity-details?number=SC042769#results|title=OSCR {{!}} Charity Details|website=OSCR|language=en|access-date=2018-10-29}}</ref>    In 2014 funding was obtained from the Growing Community Assets<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.biglotteryfund.org.uk/funding/programmes/community-assets|title=Community Assets {{!}} Big Lottery Fund|website=www.biglotteryfund.org.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-10-25}}</ref> programme of the  [[Big Lottery Fund]] (BLF) to scope and further develop this idea and prepare an application for major BLF funding.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com/news/crunch-time-in-bid-to-make-farmhouse-community-hub-1-3384175|title=Crunch time in bid to make farmhouse community hub|last=|first=|date=23 April 2014|work=Edinburgh Evening News|access-date=2018-10-25|language=en}}</ref>  The property was owned at this stage by the City of Edinburgh  Council  who in 2014 agreed to give Bridgend Inspiring Growth a years 'license to use' the property.<ref name=\":3\" /> At that point weekly volunteer activity sessions started to transform the derelict site.  The charity received grants towards community development work from City of Edinburgh Council and others.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nIn 2015 City of Edinburgh Council agreed to transfer the land and Bridgend Farmhouse to BIG for \u00a31 in one of the first cases of urban [[List of community buyouts in Scotland|asset transfer in Scotland]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.holyrood.com/articles/comment/community-empowerment-hard-work|title=Community empowerment is hard work|last=Knox|first=John|date=May 11, 2017|work=Holyrood Magazine|access-date=2018-10-26|language=en}}</ref>  This was after the Council had received 14 offers for the property, the highest being \u00a3215,000.<ref name=\":4\" /> This transfer took place  before the [[Community Empowerment (Scotland) Act 2015]] came into force in Scotland.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bridgendfarmhouse.org.uk/scotsmag.html|title=All's well down on the farm ; Scots Magazine|last=Fraser|first=Garry|date=June 2018|website=Bridgend Inspiring Growth|language=en|access-date=2018-10-25}}</ref>  The title deeds ensured that the land and building must, in perpetuity, always and only be used as a community centre for learning, eating and exercise.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nIn 2015 the charity received a grant of over \u00a31 million from the Big Lottery Fund<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.biglotteryfund.org.uk/funding/grants/recipients/GB-SC-SC042769|title=Bridgend Inspiring Growth {{!}} Big Lottery Fund|website=www.biglotteryfund.org.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-11-18}}</ref> and further grants from the [[The Edrington Group|Robertson Trust]] and [[Historic Environment Scotland]].<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theedinburghreporter.co.uk/2015/11/bridgend-farmhouse-wins-1-million-lottery-grant/|title=Bridgend Farmhouse wins \u00a31 MILLION Lottery grant|last=|first=|date=November 4, 2015|work=The Edinburgh Reporter|access-date=2018-10-25|language=en-US}}</ref> Bridgend farm opened as a community centre on 24 March 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theedinburghreporter.co.uk/2018/03/bridgend-farmhouse-opens-saturday/|title=Bridgend Farmhouse opens Saturday|last=|first=|date=March 24, 2018|work=The Edinburgh Reporter|access-date=2018-10-26|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n== Restoration ==\nThe design was developed over years of consultation with BIG and the wider community. This involved community-led design workshops and focus group discussions.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nThe intention was a sympathetic restoration, reinstating traditional historic features such as the chimney stacks and sash and case windows. It included the addition of four community workshops which were built to look like traditional farm stable barns. The Farmhouse was kept true to its original structure, and many internal features such as timber roof beams, the window shutter panels, and original staircase and handrail being retained.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bridgendfarmhouse.org.uk/farmhouse-renovation.html|title=Farmhouse Renovation|website=Bridgend Inspiring Growth|language=en|access-date=2018-12-16}}</ref>\n\nThe architects were Halliday Fraser Munro,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hfm.co.uk/|title=Halliday, Fraser, Munro|website=HFM|access-date=2019-01-06}}</ref> The design team was completed by quantity surveyors David Adamson Group, structural engineers Elliot & Co, services engineer Harley Haddow and project manager Graham Harper. Cornhill Building Services were engaged as the main contractors and, with assistance from BIG volunteers in charring and cladding on the workshops, painting and decorating, and building and installing furniture and features, delivered the restored farmhouse to the project in late 2017.<ref name=\":2\"/>\n\nIn January 2019 the project was commended for a RIBA MacEwan Award in architecture for 'the common good'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ribaj.com/macewen/macewen-award-commended-2019-bridgend-inspiring-growth-edinburgh-halliday-fraser-munro-architects|title=How good architecture helped Bridgend Farmhouse fight loneliness|last=Young|first=Eleanor|website=www.ribaj.com|language=en|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ribaj.com/macewen/macewen-award-judging-and-winners-loneliness-community-coming-together-eleanor-young|title=In praise of architecture that brings people together|last=Young|first=Eleanor|website=www.ribaj.com|language=en|access-date=2019-02-04}}</ref>\n\n== Aims ==\nThe project aims to expand opportunities for learning, healthy eating and exercise to people of all ages living in the nearby estates of [[Craigmillar]], [[Niddrie, Edinburgh|Niddrie]], [[Inch, Edinburgh|Inch]], [[Moredun]] and surrounding area.\n\nSpecifically the project aims to advance:\n\n* Development opportunities in the surrounding communities.  Specifically it seeks to improve  citizenship skills. It aims to provide opportunities for  volunteers and to provide education and training  in  outdoor skills  and improve understanding of the environment.\n* Healthy living, promoting healthier lifestyle choices to improve  physical and psychological health.  It also aims to reduce  social isolation by providing a welcoming social environment\n* Understanding of the history of the area and its heritage. \n* Equality of opportunity and promotion of diversity.\n* Awareness and increased use of   Craigmillar Castle park, and provide education about and increase awareness of   biodiversity and protection of the environment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bridgendfarmhouse.org.uk/our-vision.html#|title=Our Vision|website=Bridgend Inspiring Growth|language=en|access-date=2018-10-27}}</ref>\n\n== Facilities ==\n[[File:Bridgend Farmhouse Cafe inside 2.jpg|250px|thumb|right|Bridgend Farmhouse Cafe]]\n[[File:Bridgend Bike Shed.jpg|250px|thumb|right|Bridgend Bike Shed]]\nFacilities on the site include:\n\n* An outdoor education workshop\n* A bicycle workshop\n* An arts and crafts workshop\n* A DIY workshop\n* An exhibition/meeting room\n* Outdoor stage and performance area\n* A kitchen garden\n* External barns\n* A community caf\u00e9 \n*A training kitchen<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.bridgendfarmhouse.org.uk/our-facilities.html|title=Our Facilities|website=Bridgend Inspiring Growth|language=en|access-date=2018-10-27}}</ref>\n\n== Activities ==\nActivities and projects include 'Place, Work, Folk' a local history project, which includes creating a collection of oral history recordings from local residents<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bridgendfarmhouse.org.uk/community-history.html|title='Place, Work, Folk' Community History Project|website=Bridgend Inspiring Growth|language=en|access-date=2019-04-19}}</ref>. There are two open volunteer activity sessions every Wednesday and Sunday which involve gardening, building, woodwork, landscaping, arts and crafts, cooking and other group activities<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bridgendfarmhouse.org.uk/activity-days.html|title=Farmhouse Activity Days|website=Bridgend Inspiring Growth|language=en|access-date=2019-04-19}}</ref>. The caf\u00e9 kitchen provides training courses which can lead to qualifications in The Royal Environmental Health Institute of Scotland (REHIS) Food Hygiene, and Health & Nutrition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rehis.com/|title=The Royal Environmental Health Institute of Scotland {{!}} REHIS|website=www.rehis.com|language=en|access-date=2018-10-27}}</ref> Courses can be completed toward  a Scottish Qualification Award (SQA) in ''Working With Others''.  There is also a project called 'Real Fast Food' which involves preparing healthy locally grown food and delivering it to people who are unable to get out of their house, on an electric powered bike and trailer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bridgendfarmhouse.org.uk/real-fast-food.html|title=Real Fast Food' project 2019|website=Bridgend Inspiring Growth|language=en|access-date=2019-04-19}}</ref> There have been courses in crafts, such as lime mortar pointing and gardening.<ref name=\":1\" /> Other courses have included \"Making natural cosmetics\", \"Forest skills\", and \"Intergenerational storytelling\" which created a book of shared stories.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bridgendfarmhouse.org.uk/previous-projects.html|title=Previous Projects|website=Bridgend Inspiring Growth|language=en|access-date=2019-01-06}}</ref>\n\nThere are regular community groups and classes, including a weekly singing group<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bridgendfarmhouse.org.uk/singing-group.html|title=Bridgend Singing Group|website=Bridgend Inspiring Growth|language=en|access-date=2019-08-09}}</ref>, craft club and woodwork club.\n\nThe project's Acorn Fund  supports local people and groups with their own projects on site. These have included \"Building a wormery\", \"Wood carving\", \"A singing group\", \"A seed library\", \"Film & media training for volunteers\" and \"Medicinal dhal workshops.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bridgendfarmhouse.org.uk/big-acorn-fund.html|title=BIG Acorn Fund|website=Bridgend Inspiring Growth|language=en|access-date=2019-01-06}}</ref>\n\n== Partnerships ==\nBridgend Inspiring Growth has, or has had, collaborative partnerships with the following organisations:\n\n=== Charitable organisations ===\n{{col-begin|width=auto}}\n{{col-break}}\n* Patrick Geddes Centre<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.patrickgeddescentre.org.uk/|title=The Patrick Geddes Centre - A Unique Learning and Cultural Centre for All|website=www.patrickgeddescentre.org.uk}}</ref>\n* Health in Mind <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.health-in-mind.org.uk/|title=Health in Mind - Health in Mind is a charity promoting positive mental health and wellbeing in Scotland|first=Primitive Media LLP-|last=http://www.primitivemedia.co.uk|website=www.health-in-mind.org.uk}}</ref>\n* Arts in Healthcare <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.artinhealthcare.org.uk/|title=Transforming Scottish healthcare with art|website=Art in Healthcare}}</ref>\n* The Sorted Project <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sortedproject.co.uk/|title=Sorted: drugs & alcohol addiction recovery Edinburgh|website=www.sortedproject.co.uk}}</ref>\n* Crisis <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.crisis.org.uk/get-help/edinburgh/|title=Crisis Skylight Edinburgh - Crisis - Together we will end homelessness|website=Crisis}}</ref>\n* The Welcoming <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thewelcoming.org/about/|title=About|date=17 October 2017|website=thewelcoming.org}}</ref>\n* Positive Realities <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.positiverealities.org/|title=Positive Realities (SCIO)|website=Positive Realities (SCIO)}}</ref>\n* The Real Junk Food Project Edinburgh <ref>{{cite web|url=https://realjunkfoodedinburgh.wordpress.com/|title=The Real Junk Food Project Edinburgh|website=The Real Junk Food Project Edinburgh}}</ref>\n* Caring in Craigmillar <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.evocredbook.org.uk/organisations/caring-in-craigmillar/001b00000065upyAAA|title=EVOC|website=www.evocredbook.org.uk}}</ref>\n* Bingham 50+ <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.evocredbook.org.uk/organisations/bingham-district-50-project/001b00000065uo4AAA|title=EVOC|website=www.evocredbook.org.uk}}</ref>\n{{col-break}}\n\n* Bridgend Growing Communities  <ref>{{cite web|url=http://bridgendgrowingcommunities.org.uk/|title=Bridgend Growing Communities - Take part in community growing!|website=bridgendgrowingcommunities.org.uk}}</ref>\n* Orchard Project <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theorchardproject.org.uk/|title=The Orchard Project - Bringing community orchards to cities and towns.|website=The Orchard Project}}</ref>\n* Non-stuff Industries <ref>{{cite web|url=https://nonstuff.co.uk/|title=NonStuff Industries|website=NonStuff Industries}}</ref>\n* Teens Plus <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.teensplus.org.uk/|title=Home|website=Teens+}}</ref>\n* Edinburgh & Lothians Greenspace Trust  <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elgt.org.uk/|title=Edinburgh & Lothians Greenspace Trust - Home|website=www.elgt.org.uk}}</ref>\n* [[Royal Botanic Garden Edinburgh]]  <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rbge.org.uk/|title=The Royal Botanic Garden Edinburgh|first=Royal Botanic Garden|last=Edinburgh|website=www.rbge.org.uk}}</ref>\n* Traditional Arts and Culture Scotland  <ref>{{cite web|url=https://tracscotland.org/|title=Home - TRACS|website=tracscotland.org}}</ref>\n*Lone Fathers\u2019  Edinburgh  <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.opfs.org.uk/|title=Welcome to OPFS|website=One Parent Families Scotland}}</ref>\n\n{{col-break}}\n\n=== Schools ===\n*Castlebrae High School  <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.castlebrae.org.uk/|title=Castlebrae|website=Castlebrae}}</ref>\n*Niddrie Mill Primary School  <ref>{{cite web|url=https://niddriemill.wordpress.com/|title=Niddrie Mill Primary School|website=Niddrie Mill Primary School}}</ref>\n\n=== Universities and Colleges ===\n*Edinburgh College  <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edinburghcollege.ac.uk/|title=Welcome to Edinburgh College|website=www.edinburghcollege.ac.uk}}</ref>\n*Newbattle Abbey College <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newbattleabbeycollege.ac.uk/|title=Home|website=Newbattle Abbey College}}</ref>\n*Edinburgh University <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ed.ac.uk/home|title=The University of Edinburgh|website=The University of Edinburgh}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ed.ac.uk/local/projects/dirty-weekenders|title=Dirty Weekenders|website=The University of Edinburgh}}</ref>\n{{col-break}}\n\n=== Others ===\n\n*Power of Food Festival  <ref>{{cite web|url=https://poweroffoodfestival.wordpress.com/|title=(no title)|website=poweroffoodfestival.wordpress.com}}</ref>\n*Volunteer Centre, Edinburgh <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.volunteeredinburgh.org.uk/|title=home|website=Volunteer Edinburgh}}</ref>\n*[[Cockburn Association]] <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cockburnassociation.org.uk/|title=The Cockburn Association - For Everyone Who Loves Edinburgh|website=www.cockburnassociation.org.uk}}</ref>\n*Track Scotland <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trackscotland.co.uk/|title=TrackScotland|website=www.trackscotland.co.uk}}</ref>\n*Scottish Ecological Design Association<ref>https://www.seda.uk.net</ref>\n*Edinburgh City Council Local Area Coordination teams  <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edinburgh.gov.uk/info/20079/disabilities/476/local_area_co-ordination|title=Support for people with disabilities|first=The City of Edinburgh|last=Council|website=www.edinburgh.gov.uk}}</ref>\n{{col-end}}\n\n== Governance ==\nIn 2018 BIG became the first organisation in Scotland to transfer from a [[Scottish Charitable Incorporated Organisation]] (SCIO) to a [[Co-operative and Community Benefit Societies Act 2014|Community Benefit Society with Charitable Status]] (CCBS).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mutuals.fca.org.uk/SocietyDetails.aspx?Number=7683&Suffix=CBS|title=Financial Conduct Authority. Mutuals Public Register. Bridgend Farmhouse|last=|first=|date=18 May 2018|website=mutuals.fca.org.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-11-26}}</ref> Under this model members buy shares to become part-owners of the land and project and each member has one vote.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://communityshares.org.uk/resources/handbook/community-benefit-societies|title=Community benefit societies|last=|first=|date=25 October 2013|work=Community Shares|access-date=2018-11-26|language=en}}</ref> The first Community Share Issue in 2018 raised over \u00a370,000 from 400 members<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thirdforcenews.org.uk/tfn-news/community-project-smashes-funding-target|title=Community project smashes funding target|last=Jones|first=Gareth|date=23 November 2018|work=Third Force News|access-date=2018-12-02|language=en}}</ref> and these  members  have rights to decide the future of the organisation, vote at the [[Annual general meeting|AGM]] and advise on strategic direction and management.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/edinburgh-community-buys-70-000-shares-to-rescue-farmhouse-1-4833749|title=Edinburgh community buys \u00a370,000 shares to rescue farmhouse|last=Ross|first=Shan|date=22 November 2018|work=The Scotsman|access-date=2018-11-25|language=en}}</ref>\n\nBIG has a board of twelve trustees all of whom are volunteers. At least 50% of the Trustees must live within the area of benefit and no decision can be made at a Board level without a local majority being present.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.bridgendfarmhouse.org.uk/our-journey.html|title=Our Journey|website=Bridgend Inspiring Growth|language=en|access-date=2018-11-11}}</ref>\n\nThe organisation has democratic structures which enable volunteers and members to direct the work of the project. There are three working groups which meet monthly; Buildings and Land, Activities and Events, and Business. These are a monthly forum for volunteers to work together and make collective decisions.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Awards and recognition ==\nIn January 2019 the project was commended for a RIBA MacEwan Award in architecture for 'the common good'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ribaj.com/macewen/macewen-award-commended-2019-bridgend-inspiring-growth-edinburgh-halliday-fraser-munro-architects|title=How good architecture helped Bridgend Farmhouse fight loneliness|last=Young|first=Eleanor|website=www.ribaj.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ribaj.com/macewen/macewen-award-judging-and-winners-loneliness-community-coming-together-eleanor-young|title=In praise of architecture that brings people together|last=Young|first=Eleanor|website=www.ribaj.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-12}}</ref>\n\nBridgend Farmhouse was chosen as an example of good practice in the Scottish Government's 'A Connected Scotland; Strategy for tackling social isolation and loneliness and building stronger communities' 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.scot/publications/connected-scotland-strategy-tackling-social-isolation-loneliness-building-stronger-social-connections/|title=A Connected Scotland: our strategy for tackling social isolation and loneliness and building stronger social connections - gov.scot|website=www.gov.scot|access-date=2019-04-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/politics/new-strategy-to-tackle-loneliness-launched-by-scottish-government-1-4845952|title=New strategy to tackle loneliness launched by Scottish government|website=www.scotsman.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-12}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019 the project received a 'Special Commendation' in the Scottish Council for Voluntary Organisations (SCVO) Charity of the Year awards in the 'Celebrating Communities' category.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scvo.org.uk/scottish-charity-awards|title=SCVO Charity of the year awards 2019|website=scvo.org.uk|access-date=2019-08-09}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scvo.org.uk/scottish-charity-awards/finalists-2019/celebrating-communities/p_award_bridgend-farmhouse|title=SCVO Finalists 2019 - Bridgend Farmhouse|website=scvo.org.uk|access-date=2019-08-09}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n* Speedy, Tom ''Guide to Craigmillar and its environs''. (1894) Selkirk, George Lewis and Son. p61\n* Speedy, Tom ''Craigmillar and its environs''. (1902) Selkirk, George Lewis and Son. p213-215\n* Geddie, John ''The Fringes of Edinburgh ( 1932 )'' Edinburgh, W & R Chambers.p129\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [http://www.bridgendfarmhouse.org.uk/ Bridgend Inspiring Growth website]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCo3QPKKFDd_9crdjXXp_f2g/videos/ Bridgend Farmhouse Video Archive]\n* [https://www.oscr.org.uk/about-charities/search-the-register/charity-details?number=SC042769#results Office of the Scottish Charity Regulator:. Bridgend Inspiring Growth details]\n* [https://mutuals.fca.org.uk/SocietyDetails.aspx?Number=7683&Suffix=CBS Registration of the society with the Financial Conducts Authority]\n\n[[Category:Social centres in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Charities based in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Charities based in Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Organisations based in Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Restaurants in Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Community buyouts in Scotland]]\n", "name_user": "KayNAt169", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added link to a video where the Darlings give dates for their time at the farmhouse", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bridgend_Farmhouse_Community_Project"}
{"title_page": "Fixing Dinner", "text_new": "{{short description|Canadian reality television series}}\n{{Unreferenced|date=December 2009}}\n{{Infobox television |\n| show_name = Fixing Dinner\n| caption = \n| runtime = 30 minutes\n| creator = Sandi Richard\n| starring  = [[Sandi Richard]]\n| country = [[Canada]]\n| network = [[Food Network Canada]]\n|}}\n\n'''''Fixing Dinner''''' is a Canadian [[food reality television series]] on [[Food Network Canada]], airing on [[AmericanLife TV Network|AmericanLife]] in the [[United States]]. Host [[Sandi Richard]] comes \"to the rescue\" of a family that can't cope with making healthy, fresh dinners, and teaches how to counteract their lack of time.\n\nThe show follows a standard format - first, a 'help us' video is shown, detailing the problems the family faces. Sandi comes to their house to discuss the situation in more detail, and to inspect the kitchen. She identifies the most stressful or time crunched day of the week, labeled 'Fright Night'.\n\nShe returns several days later with a menu plan of a month's worth of meals. Magnets symbolizing the various family members and the foods they will cook are placed on the fridge as she introduces this week's menu.\n\nA shopping trip follows, with Sandi recommending various prepared or partially prepared foods as time savers (such as store-bought sauces, precut vegetables). In some episodes, a brief overview of how Sandi has reorganized the kitchen is shown.\n\nThen Sandi proceeds to walk each family member through the meals they are preparing this week. The family is left alone to handle 'Fright Night' according to her plans.\n\nTo conclude the show, Sandi returns a month later to find out how the monthly meal plan has worked. Families always claim improvement on the problem Sandi was sent to solve. Common problems are too much fast food, lack of time to prepare dinner, one member of the family being solely responsible for meals, lack of variety, picky eaters and disparate schedules. Before the credits begin, she always ends with the phrase, \"Fixing dinner isn't just about food, it's about family\".\n\n[[Category:Food reality television series]]\n[[Category:Canadian reality television series]]\n[[Category:Food Network (Canadian TV channel) series]]\n\n\n{{Canada-tv-prog-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Canadian reality television series}}\n{{Unreferenced|date=December 2009}}\n{{Infobox television |\n| show_name = Fixing Dinner\n| caption = \n| runtime = 30 minutes\n| creator = Sandi Richard\n| starring  = [[Sandi Richard]]\n| country = [[Canada]]\n| network = [[Food Network Canada]]\n|}}\n\n'''''Fixing Dinner''''' is a Canadian [[food reality television series]] on [[Food Network Canada]], airing on [[AmericanLife TV Network|AmericanLife]] in the [[United States]]. Host [[Sandi Richard]] comes \"to the rescue\" of a family that can't cope with making healthy, fresh dinners, and teaches how to counteract their lack of time.\n\nThe show follows a standard format - first, a 'help us' video is shown, detailing the problems the family faces. Sandi comes to their house to discuss the situation in more detail, and to inspect the kitchen. She identifies the most stressful or time crunched day of the week, labeled 'Fright Night'.\n\nShe returns several days later with a menu plan of a month's worth of meals. Magnets symbolizing the various family members and the foods they will cook are placed on the fridge as she introduces this week's menu.\n\nA shopping trip follows, with Sandi recommending various prepared or partially prepared foods as time savers (such as store-bought sauces, precut vegetables). In some episodes, a brief overview of how Sandi has reorganized the kitchen is shown.\n\nThen Sandi proceeds to walk each family member through the meals they are preparing this week. The family is left alone to handle 'Fright Night' according to her plans.\n\nTo conclude the show, Sandi returns a month later to find out how the monthly meal plan has worked. Families always claim improvement on the problem Sandi was sent to solve. Common problems are too much fast food, lack of time to prepare dinner, one member of the family being solely responsible for meals, lack of variety, picky eaters and disparate schedules. Before the credits begin, she always ends with the phrase, \"Fixing dinner isn't just about food, it's about family\".\n\n[[Category:Food reality television series]]\n[[Category:Canadian reality television series]]\n[[Category:Food Network (Canadian TV channel) series]]\n[[Category:Canadian cooking television series]]\n\n\n{{Canada-tv-prog-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:duplicate categorization; already in subcat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fixing_Dinner"}
