{"title_page": "Chips Hardy", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| image       = \n| birth_name  = Edward John Hardy III\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1950|1|23}}\n| birth_place = [[London]], England\n| residence   = \n| occupation  = Screenwriter, novelist, playwright\n| spouse      = Elizabeth Ann Hardy\n| children    = [[Tom Hardy]]\n| yearsactive = \n}}\n\n'''Edward John''' \"'''Chips'''\" '''Hardy''' '''III'''(born 23 January 1950) is an English [[screenwriter]], novelist, playwright, and [[creative director]]. He and Elizabeth Ann, his wife, are the parents of actor [[Tom Hardy]], with whom Hardy worked on [[BBC One]]'s drama series ''[[Taboo (2017 TV series)|Taboo]]'', as the co-creator, a writer and a consulting producer.\n\n== Career ==\nAlongside a career in advertising as an award-winning Global Creative Director, Hardy has written for television, film, theatre, novels and stand-up material. Productions include a children\u2019s television series with a talking chair called ''[[Helping Henry]]'' and [[About Face (TV series)|''About Face'']], a television drama with Maureen Lipman. Hardy also won a British Comedy Award for his work with Irish comedian [[Dave Allen (comedian)|Dave Allen]].\n\nIn 2007, Hardy\u2019s novel ''Each Day A Small Victory'' was published in the form of frontline despatches from amongst the embattled wildlife in an English country lay-by, illustrated by Oscar Grillo.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Chips-Hardy/e/B001JP1RPM|title=Amazon.co.uk: Chips Hardy: Books, Biogs, Audiobooks, Discussions|website=www.amazon.co.uk|access-date=2017-03-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/booksblog/2009/nov/10/animal-noir|title=Get your claws on animal noir|last=Munshower|first=Suzanne|date=2009-11-10|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-03-08|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n''Blue on Blue'', Hardy\u2019s darkly comic play on self-harm, was first showcased at the Latchmere 503 in London in 2007.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestage.co.uk/features/interviews/2016/chips-hardy-good-play-can-point-things-without-wave-flag/|title=Chips Hardy: 'A good play can point things out without having to wave a flag' {{!}} Interviews {{!}} The Stage|date=2016-04-26|work=The Stage|access-date=2017-03-08|language=en-US}}</ref> The play was revived in 2016 at the [[Tristan Bates Theatre|Tristan Bates]] in London in partnership with [[Blesma, The Limbless Veterans|BLESMA]], the British Limbless Ex-serviceman\u2019s Association.<ref name=\":1\" /> In 2008, Hardy\u2019s one woman dysfunctional Cabaret, ''There\u2019s Something In The Fridge that Wants To Kill Me!'', ran notably at the [[Edinburgh Festival]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.officiallondontheatre.co.uk/london-shows/show/item101295/theres-something-in-the-fridge-that-wants-to-kill-me/|title=There's Something In The Fridge That Wants To Kill Me!|website=www.officiallondontheatre.co.uk|access-date=2017-03-08}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, inspired by an idea from his son Tom Hardy, Chips Hardy and Tom created the story that was to become the 2017 eight-part series'' [[Taboo (2017 TV series)|Taboo]]''. Hardy is the co-creator, a writer and a consulting producer.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/01/03/tom-hardy-wins-dream-acting-role-convincing-dad-write/|title=Tom Hardy wins dream acting role - after convincing his dad to create it for him|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2017-03-08|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.flickeringmyth.com/2017/01/interview-tom-hardy-and-chips-hardy-talk-taboo/|title=Interview: Tom Hardy and Chips Hardy talk Taboo|date=2017-01-03|work=Flickering Myth|access-date=2017-03-11|language=en-US}}</ref> His work on the screenplay for [[Taboo (2017 TV series)|Taboo]]  earned him the [[Writers' Guild of Great Britain|Writer\u2019s Guild of Great Britain]] award for ''Best Long Form TV Drama'' in 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://writersguild.org.uk/writers-guild-awards-winners-2018/|title=Writers\u2019 Guild Awards winners 2018 - Writers' Guild of Great Britain|date=2018-01-15|work=Writers' Guild of Great Britain|access-date=2018-02-26|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0362609}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hardy, Chips}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English television writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| image       = \n| birth_name  = Edward John Hardy\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1950|1|23}}\n| birth_place = [[London]], England\n| residence   = \n| occupation  = Screenwriter, novelist, playwright\n| spouse      = Elizabeth Ann Hardy\n| children    = [[Tom Hardy]]\n| yearsactive = \n}}\n\n'''Edward John''' \"'''Chips'''\" '''Hardy''' (born 23 January 1950) is an English [[screenwriter]], novelist, playwright, and [[creative director]]. He and Elizabeth Ann, his wife, are the parents of actor [[Tom Hardy]], with whom Hardy worked on [[BBC One]]'s drama series ''[[Taboo (2017 TV series)|Taboo]]'', as the co-creator, a writer and a consulting producer.\n\n== Career ==\nAlongside a career in advertising as an award-winning Global Creative Director, Hardy has written for television, film, theatre, novels and stand-up material. Productions include a children\u2019s television series with a talking chair called ''[[Helping Henry]]'' and [[About Face (TV series)|''About Face'']], a television drama with Maureen Lipman. Hardy also won a British Comedy Award for his work with Irish comedian [[Dave Allen (comedian)|Dave Allen]].\n\nIn 2007, Hardy\u2019s novel ''Each Day A Small Victory'' was published in the form of frontline despatches from amongst the embattled wildlife in an English country lay-by, illustrated by Oscar Grillo.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Chips-Hardy/e/B001JP1RPM|title=Amazon.co.uk: Chips Hardy: Books, Biogs, 